1. Introduction¶

1.1 Motivation:
    Happiness appears to be an increasingly important factor to our existence as quality of life has increased. People have begun to embrace being happy in the moment. As we begin to optimize and desire more of this intangible qualia, we as a species have begun to categorize and break "happiness" down into what appears to be relevant components in a desire to further our understanding. While there are many individualistic things one can do to improve their happiness such as practicing meditation and gratefulness, this tutorial will attempt to examine larger nation-wide factors that can impact happiness.

1.2 Libraries Used:
    Pandas: used to represent and see data in dataframes
    Collections: used for general data structure manipulation
    Matplotlib: used generate data plots
    SKLearn: used to analyze data and predict factors
    Numpy: used to support data and pandas
    Statistics: more generalized statistical methods
    Scipy: used for some statistical analysis
    Statsmodels: used for additional statistical analysis
    Seaborn: used for additional data visualization

3. Data Management/Representation¶

The data from Kaggle is kind enough to provide a quick-preview. It appears that each year's data set is non-homogenous. Let's try to get them all uniform for more easy comparisons. The more recent data from 2018/2019 formats seem to be more concise and make more sense than previous years. Extraneous data will be ignored and there will be a focus on GDP, Social Support, Life Expectancy, Freedom, Geneoristy, and Perception of Governmental Corruption.

In [49]:
Years = [2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]
dataframes = [data_15, data_16, data_17, data_18, data_19]

for i,y in zip(dataframes, Years):
    correlation = i.corr()
    sn.heatmap(correlation, annot = True)
    plt.title(y)
    plt.show()

From the heatmaps indicating correlation, it's quite clear that most things have a positive correlation with regards to the Happiness Score. Not surprisingly, GDP per capita, social support, life expectancy, freedom, and perception of lower governmental corruption are all correlated with feeling happy. What is surprising is generosity has the least correlation with happiness of all the other factors and is GDP agnostic-as in everyone has similar levels of generosity.

map_osm = folium.Map(location=[54.53, 17.25], zoom_start=2)
#arbitrary cutoffs from 105-155
for i, row in data_15.iterrows():
    if (row['Overall Rank'] <= 25):
        if(row['Country or Region'] in locations.values):
            lat = locations.loc[locations['country'] == row['Country or Region'], 'latitude']
            lon = locations.loc[locations['country'] == row['Country or Region'], 'longitude']
            folium.Marker(
                location = [float(lat),float(lon)],
                popup = "{}".format(row['Country or Region']),
                icon = folium.Icon(color="blue"),
            ).add_to(map_osm)
    if (row['Overall Rank'] >= 130):
        if(row['Country or Region'] in locations.values):
            lat = locations.loc[locations['country'] == row['Country or Region'], 'latitude']
            lon = locations.loc[locations['country'] == row['Country or Region'], 'longitude']
            folium.Marker(
                location = [float(lat),float(lon)],
                popup = "{}".format(row['Country or Region']),
                icon = folium.Icon(color="red"),
            ).add_to(map_osm)

def avg(x):
    return sum(x)/len(x)
In [178]:
dataframes = [data_15, data_16, data_17, data_18, data_19]

for country in intersection:
    ranks, scores, GDPs, socials, LEs, freedoms, gen, perceptions = ([] for i in range(8))
    for dataframe in dataframes:
        ranks.append(int(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Overall Rank']))
        scores.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Score']))
        GDPs.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['GDP per capita']))
        socials.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Social Support']))
        LEs.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Healthy Life Expectancy']))
        freedoms.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Freedom to Make Life Choices']))
        gen.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Generosity']))
        perceptions.append(float(dataframe[dataframe['Country or Region'] == country]['Perceptions of Corruption']))
    

    Avg_Rank = avg(ranks)
    Avg_Score = avg(scores)
    Avg_GDP = avg(GDPs)
    Avg_Social = avg(socials)
    Avg_LE = avg(LEs)
    Avg_Freedom = avg(freedoms)
    Avg_Generosity = avg(gen)
    Avg_Perceptions = avg(perceptions)
    
    to_add = pd.DataFrame([[Avg_Rank, country, Avg_Score, Avg_GDP, Avg_Social, Avg_LE, Avg_Freedom, Avg_Generosity, Avg_Perceptions]],
                          columns = ['Overall Rank', 'Country or Region', 'Score', 'GDP per capita', 'Social Support', 'Healthy Life Expectancy', 
                                     'Freedom to Make Life Choices', 'Generosity', 'Perceptions of Corruption'])
    merged = merged.append(to_add, ignore_index=True)
